The paper deals with the performance analysis of a wireless communication system with interference, fading, and spatial correlation. This falls under the domain of information theory (cs.IT) and networked systems (cs.NI). The use of stochastic geometry to model interference and the analysis of correlation make it relevant to the sub-category of spatial interference (cs.SI). The paper also uses mathematical tools such as probability theory and statistics, making it relevant to the sub-category of mathematical analysis (cs.MA). Finally, the paper discusses the performance gains of different combining techniques, which can be seen as a game-theoretic problem, making it relevant to the sub-category of game theory (cs.GT).
